    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/03-pretraining/17-end-to-end-pretrain-recipe.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The whole run is a chain of format-transforming stages (text -> tokens -> uint16 .bin -> model -> checkpoint -> samples); every stage's *internals* were built in another chapter, and THIS chapter is only the glue that makes the artifacts hand off cleanly.; The uint16 shard is a CONTRACT: prepare.py's writer dtype must exactly equal ShardedTokenLoader's memmap dtype, and the loader slices (ctx+1)-token windows that split into x = w[:-1] and y = w[1:] (the one-position target shift). A dtype mismatch reinterprets bytes as garbage; a missing shift makes loss stick at ln(vocab).; The SAME train.py scales across four hardware tiers; what changes is not the model/loss/schedule code but the launch flags and the sharding strategy -- 'use the least sharding that fits': DDP (replicate) while state fits one GPU, climb to FSDP FULL_SHARD (shard params/grads/optimizer), then HYBRID_SHARD when the inter-node link becomes the bottleneck.; The effective batch is assembled from four multiplied knobs (local_bsz x ctx x world_size x grad_accum), and that tokens/step number divides the Chinchilla token budget to set the total step count against which the LR schedule is computed.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  pretrain-shard-contract-window\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
