    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/04-kernels-efficiency/07-quantization-ptq.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Quantization maps floats to a small integer grid via a scale s (and optional zero-point z), and the rounding error is proportional to s, which is proportional to the tensor's dynamic RANGE \u2014 so one giant value poisons everyone.; Granularity (per-tensor -> per-channel -> per-group) buys fidelity by fitting each scale to a smaller, more homogeneous slice, at a tiny storage cost.; Activation outliers: past ~6B params a few feature channels run 10-100x the rest; they inflate a per-tensor scale and crush normal values to zero \u2014 and they live in activations, not weights, which is why weight-only INT4 is nearly free.; GPTQ minimizes the LAYER OUTPUT error, not the weight error: quantize columns left-to-right, and after committing each rounding error, nudge the not-yet-quantized columns via H^-1 to absorb it.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  llm-int8-decomposition\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
