    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/04-kernels-efficiency/08-quantization-formats-qat.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Quantize/dequantize is an affine map q = round(w/s) + z, w_hat = s(q - z); per-element error is bounded by s/2, so finer granularity and better calibration win by shrinking s.; Fewer bits helps because autoregressive decode is memory-bandwidth-bound: weight-only quant just moves fewer HBM bytes (arithmetic stays FP16), while W+A additionally runs the GEMM on low-precision integer units.; NF4 places its 16 code points at the quantiles of the normal distribution, spending resolution where weights actually cluster (near zero) instead of uniformly like INT4 -- optimal for normally-distributed weights.; LLM.int8 keeps the tiny fraction of outlier activation channels in FP16 and quantizes the rest to INT8 (mixed-precision decomposition), so a few huge-magnitude channels can't wreck the whole matmul.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  quant-llm-int8-outlier-decomposition\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
