    "draw": "You are the FIGURE DRAWER (Sonnet 5) for the web textbook \"The LLM Stack\".\nChapter (read the relevant sections for exact framing/terminology): /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/content/05-posttraining-alignment/02-chat-templates-packing.md\n\nAuthor these figures. Do them ONE AT A TIME; finish and verify each before the next. Do NOT stop\nearly \u2014 complete every task or list what you couldn't in figures_skipped.\n\n  NEW  [static]  name=chattmpl-template-anatomy\n       concept: Anatomy of one rendered conversation turn: special delimiter tokens vs plain role string vs content, the prompt boundary, and the appended generation prompt at inference.\n       placement: after 'The Major Template Families \u2192 ChatML (place marker right after the two-turn ChatML example block)'\n       brief: A horizontal 'token ribbon' dissecting one complete assistant turn in ChatML, reading left to right as a sequence of adjacent token chips: [<|im_start|>] [assistant] [\\n] [content tokens \u2026] [<|im_end|>] [\\n]. Give the three categories three distinct chip styles and a small legend: (a) SPECIAL delimiter tokens \u2014 <|im_start|>, <|im_end|> \u2014 emphasised as single indivisible vocabulary entries; (b) ROLE STRING \u2014 the word 'assistant' + newline \u2014 marked 'ordinary text, tokenised normally, NOT a special token'; (c) CONTENT \u2014 the actual reply tokens.\n\nAbove the ribbon show a compact preceding context (a collapsed user turn drawn as a faded strip ending in <|im_end|>) so the reader sees this assistant turn in place. Draw a vertical 'prompt boundary' line falling exactly between the role header (<|im_start|>assistant\\n) and the first content token, labelled 'prompt boundary \u2014 everything left is prompt (masked), everything right is generated (supervised)'. This visually ties the delimiter anatomy to the loss-mask figure that follows.\n\nBelow the ribbon add a small inset labelled 'at inference' showing the server appends just the header '<|im_start|>assistant\\n' after the last user turn and the model decodes content until it emits <|im_end|>. Keep it to a single turn so chips stay large and readable; render the literal token strings monospace. Theme-safe styling via theme tokens/currentColor, the three chip styles must remain distinguishable in both light and dark, all chips and the boundary label inside the viewBox with no overlap. Static frame conveys everything.\n\nFIGURE AUTHORING SPEC (follow exactly \u2014 correct, beautiful, theme-safe):\nOUTPUT FILE: a self-contained figures/<NAME>.html: a `<figure class=\"viz\" id=\"fig-<NAME>\">` with\n  optionally `<button class=\"viz-replay\" type=\"button\">/replay</button>`, exactly one inline\n  `<svg viewBox=\"0 0 W H\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"...\">` (W ~ 660-820; H to fit), and a\n  `<figcaption>` with a <b>bold lead sentence</b> + 1-2 sentences on the takeaway.\n  No <script>, no external images. A scoped `<style>` (selectors prefixed #fig-<NAME>) is fine.\nLAYOUT: EVERYTHING inside the viewBox with ~10px padding \u2014 text must NOT run past edges (it clips).\n  No illegible overlaps (>= ~16px gaps between groups). Clear left-to-right or top-to-bottom order.\nCOLOR (must work in BOTH themes \u2014 NEVER hardcode a primary color): prefer classes v-fill, v-accent,\n  v-accent-s, v-stroke, v-grid, v-muted, v-label, v-mono; or inline `var(--accent)` /\n  `stroke=\"var(--good,#2f9e6e)\"`. Vars: --accent,--accent-2,--ink-soft,--muted,--good(#2f9e6e),\n  --warn(#e0a106),--accent2(#3b82f6),--surface,--surface-3,--border-2. Raw hex is FORBIDDEN as a\n  primary color (breaks one theme); hex allowed ONLY as the fallback inside var(...).\nFONTS: `font:600 13px var(--sans,sans-serif)`; code/labels `var(--mono,monospace)`.\nANIMATION (enhancement only \u2014 the figure MUST be fully clear as a STATIC image; never rely on motion):\n  stage reveals via `data-anim=\"1\"..\"5\"` on top-level groups; `class=\"viz-draw\" style=\"--len:NNN\"`\n  draws a line; `class=\"viz-sweep\"` sweeps; `class=\"viz-pulse\"` pulses. For a `long-animation`, use a\n  longer ordered sequence of data-anim stages that walks through the process step by step, but every\n  stage's end-state must still read correctly as a static frame.\nTEXT SAFETY: ASCII only inside the SVG (no fancy Unicode arrows/operators/emoji/math-alphanumerics \u2014\n  they tofu). Use ->, <=, x, pi, sqrt written out, etc. Small illustrative integers only; invent NO\n  benchmark numbers. role=\"img\" + a one-sentence aria-label.\n\nFor EACH figure:\n1. Write (NEW) or Edit (refine/replace) /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html per the brief and SPEC.\n2. VISUALLY VERIFY: `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook, then READ\n   /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Fix anything clipped, overlapping, low-contrast in\n   either theme, or that misrepresents the idea. Iterate up to 3 passes until both look clean.\n3. For a NEW figure, insert the marker `{{fig:<NAME>}}` on its own line (blank line before/after)\n   into content/05-posttraining-alignment/02-chat-templates-packing.md at the planned placement, using Edit. Change NOTHING else in the chapter.\n   (refine/replace keep their existing marker \u2014 do not add a duplicate.)\n\nReturn the structured result: figures_done (names finished + verified) and figures_skipped (with why).",
    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/02-chat-templates-packing.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: A chat template is a deterministic function that flattens role/content pairs into ONE token stream punctuated by special delimiter tokens (im_start/im_end, header_id/eot_id), and it defines a prompt boundary: everything up to the assistant content is prompt, the assistant content is what the model must generate. Train and inference must produce the byte-identical string.; Train-on-completions-only: the loss mask sets labels=-100 on every prompt/role/user/tool token and supervises ONLY assistant content (plus its stop token). In multi-turn dialogue EVERY assistant turn is supervised, not just the last. Masking removes gradient, not context \u2014 causal attention still lets each assistant token see all prior tokens.; Padding wastes compute: right-padding every short example up to max_length fills most of each row with dead PAD tokens the model still spends FLOPs on. Sequence packing concatenates several variable-length examples into one fixed-length row, driving utilisation from ~1/4 up toward ~90%.; Cross-document attention leakage is the central correctness hazard of packing: with a plain causal mask, the first token of document 2 can attend to the last token of document 1 \u2014 a dependency that never exists at inference. The fix is a block-diagonal causal mask (or Flash-Attention cu_seqlens), which confines attention to within each document, plus per-document position_id resets.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  chattmpl-template-anatomy\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
