    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/04-peft-prompt-merging.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Soft prompting makes the prompt EMBEDDINGS trainable while the backbone stays frozen; gradients reach only the k soft tokens (already served by the existing figure).; The three input/activation-space PEFT methods differ by WHERE they intervene: prompt tuning at the input layer only, prefix tuning by prepending learned K/V at EVERY attention layer, IA3 by element-wise rescaling of K, V, and FFN activations at every layer.; A task vector is just the delta between a fine-tune and its base (theta_ft - theta_base); skills can be ADDED, SUBTRACTED, and COMPOSED by arithmetic on these vectors in weight space.; Merging only works because fine-tunes from the SAME base checkpoint live in a shared low-loss basin, so their interpolation stays low-loss for multiple tasks; different-base models live in unrelated basins and merging is noise.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  ties-merge-pipeline\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
