    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/10-reasoning-test-time-compute.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Reasoning is a search problem: the correct answer lies at the END of a PATH through a reasoning tree, not at the top of the next-token distribution \u2014 more test-time compute buys a wider/deeper search of that tree.; Chain-of-thought works by externalising intermediate state into the context window: it turns a fixed-depth single forward pass into a variable-depth sequential computation, because each emitted token becomes an attention target for later tokens (chained shallow steps = deep computation).; Self-consistency (majority vote over N samples) amplifies a STRONG signal but cannot rescue a fundamentally weak model \u2014 the binomial makes this concrete.; A Process Reward Model scores EVERY step and exposes the weakest link, giving a richer search/training signal than an Outcome Reward Model, which sees only the final answer and can be fooled by a lucky-but-unsound solution.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  test-time-scaling-curves\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
